Table 10
In this table the origin, or presumed origin, of the major invertebrate pests scoring 10+ or more (Table 3) is given where possible. Where a species has long been widespread it is often difficult to presume its origin, although detailed study of the literature on it and related species may well add further precision, particularly if supplemented by information on its specific (or reasonably specific) natural enemies. Experience has shown that the largest number

of these usually occur in the area of origin of a species. Also, if a phytophagous pest is specific, or reasonably specific, to a particular host plant, it is quite likely that it originated in the same region as that plant.
In general, those pests that originated outside the oceanic Pacific are far more likely to be suitable targets for classical biological control than those native to the region.

The Major Invertebrate Pests and Weeds of Agriculture and Plantation Forestry in the Southern and Western Pacific

51

